Its 11:30 pm last night, and I’m flicking on the light switch in my studio that fire two bright white LED lights at the ceiling. I step into the space holding a box of “fancy cookies” and several sleeves of florals from @jewelosco. And I’m shooting.⁣
⁣
Because my studio is clean, and the flowers I bought today are pristine, and Christmas is soon. And I just can’t help myself. ⁣
⁣
I never want to lose this spark. This overwhelming need to create. The thought than I can walk into this room, and leave a few hours later, and have created a piece of art that will live on?⁣
That’s wild⁣
⁣
It makes me so thankful to be able to practice. That my creative outlet exists in a room⁣
In the middle of my house⁣
In the midst of such day to day chaos⁣
And in the quiet stillness of midnight⁣
⁣
Do I stay up too late, drinking wine and placing things in a scene and moving them again and again and again, when I know our kid will need me in the morning, and I’ll have just laid my head down four hours earlier? Sure do. ⁣
But these flowers, and this holiday season, can’t last. So I’ll probably be here again tonight, capturing the magic of the season while the world around me sleeps 🥰🎄

One Valentine’s Day, nearly ten years ago, we awoke before dawn and slipped out the door of my parent’s house. We watched the sunrise over 93 as I sobbed, conflicted by emotions. You placed a hand on my knee and told me we got this— Two big optimistic hearts and two very small dogs in a ‘04 Civic headed west.⁣
⁣
We were there in LA a brief blip.⁣
Rough, tumbling waves crashing ashore Thousand Steps beach. An oppressively hot summer in the valley. Vibrant, hot pink roses blooming in our neighbor’s front yard. A pizza and a glass of wine at Mozza every Wednesday with you behind the bar.⁣
⁣
A phone call from home that changed everything.⁣
A girl different than the one whom you asked to marry.⁣
⁣
I went to LA with big, ambitious dreams and a fleeting sense of disbelief. ⁣
And went back to Massachusetts a year and a half later with hearts as heavy as the boxes placed on the concrete floor of the loft. You held me, literally and figuratively, through the toughest moments of my life. Through interstate moves and monumental career shifts and moments of pulling up to the curb of a hospital. ⁣
⁣
But also through ten pm dinners, cooked with meticulous detail. Two person game nights and podcast recordings. Road trips and fights and makeups and so ⁣
many ⁣
concerts.⁣
⁣
It’s been almost fifteen years and so much has changed. ⁣
But hot pink roses will always make me think of Brandon and Kim’s front yard, our brief time in Los Angeles, and what you’ve done for me.⁣
My fuzzy valentine 💕

Just touched back down in Chicago, and man that flight was quick— Carried by swift winds and perhaps my willpower to cuddle my son, I’m already home again.

And it feels almost unclear if this week was even real. LA drove us out with cold and unrelenting rain this morning, as we piled our (ironically rented) convertible with luggage too big for its size. Was I really on this beautiful beach just four days ago? Did I really meet two of my dearest internet friends? Did I finally get to hold one of my BFF’s new babies? Was it, really, all a dream?

I mean I guess if you mean dream
Like in the sense of the phrase “dream job”

Then yeah… it was.

Show of hands - who has worked in the service industry? 🙋‍♀️ what’s your favorite memory or your biggest disaster? I’ve got some of both.

I spent part of high school and all of college waiting tables, pouring beers, bussing plates, serving others. There was a time in my twenties, a few years into my “real job” that I longed for the hustle and bustle of a bar so much that I took a second gig at a piano bar by Fenway, and spent my Friday and Saturday nights slinging cocktails and dancing for crazy crowds of bachelorette parties and baseball fans. 

I think once you’re in it, you never really leave. You’ll always be the guest that is more than understanding, leaves the best tip, tries to feel like a regular. 

There was also one time when I first started that I dropped a freezing cold 22 ounce beer on a guest. I’ll never forget that, either. 

Shooting restaurants is such a privilege. To capture a space, the food, the drinks and the vibe in a few short hours feels like creating magic. Hoping that’s what I can create for all my service industry clients. 💫🍴📸

Well well well.
If it isn’t July 10th, and the last year of my thirties, just sneaking up on us already. 

I thought by now I’d have some sage wisdom to impart. You know, like I’ve learned a lot in thirty nine years but the most important thing was…

I don’t know. Maybe it’s because I started this third decade of my life two days into trauma that would soon define my life and my character. Maybe I don’t know what constitutes as wise decisions because all I can reason is that I am, still, quite lucky to be where I ended up.

Maybe I can’t reflect without sorrow and I’m not about that today. 

All I know is I started my thirties with compartmentalized creativity. I didn’t think this would ever work, any of it. And it took feeling like literally your entire world could crash tomorrow to find those guts and go for it. 

If you want to give me a birthday gift, do something bold and reckless. If you want to give me two, call your mom ♥️

Hey it’s been a min 👋 ⁣
Summer was crazy. ⁣
⁣
I lost my biggest client. ⁣
⁣
My mom had a brief hospital stay (she’s home and doing alright again now). ⁣
⁣
I signed a bunch of new work.⁣
⁣
We spent entirely too much time at a lake house we don’t own (love you thank you @dirtyquiltshandmade)⁣
⁣
I, as always, shot personal projects until 3am in my studio, while everyone in my house slept, and it was so quiet you could hear the hum of the LED lights, aimed at the ceiling, drawing every bug that had been hiding into the room to⁣ congregate and watch me work. ⁣
⁣
Beau got covid. I got covid. Matty got covid. Everything I had avoided so vigilantly for three years came straight through our front door the week our kid started daycare and we just had to deal and roll with the punches once again.⁣
⁣
The end of summer always makes me really sad— saying goodbye to late sunsets and long days and our pool and that golden hour that feels warmer, more nostalgic. ⁣
⁣
This year it’s feeling like a fresh start. Like I’m about to embark on eleventeenth grade where I finally know what I want to study and how to present myself and what I’m doing (maybe?) ⁣
⁣
Anyway, watermelon always feels like late summer/early fall and mimosas are a Sunday staple. This was delicious, go make yourself one and cheers to next season & rolling with it 🥂

Can we believe it’s just about holiday season again?? Let’s kick it off with a cocktail! #ad ⁣
⁣
This @empress1908gin elderflower sour feels so fancy, but comes together so quickly! Shake one up for Friendsgiving or just a little treat for yourself on a Friday. It’s called self care, friends. ⁣
⁣
Empress & Elderflower Sour⁣
2 oz @empress1908gin⁣
1 oz elderflower liqueur⁣
1 oz lemon juice⁣
.5 oz simple syrup⁣
1 egg white⁣
⁣
Combine all ingredients in a shaker and dry shake (with no ice) vigorously for about a minute. (Pro tip! If you want to forego that arm workout, you can also use an immersion blender and give it a good blitz for 30-45 seconds!!)⁣
⁣
Add ice to the shaker and shake vigorously again for about 30 seconds. Strain into a coupe glass and garnish with an edible flower. Enjoy your #EmpressGin elderflower sour! Oh and #sipresponsibly, yeah?

So much of this art form is finding a moment to steal to act on your inspiration 🍎 ⁣
⁣
I somehow missed the sticker on these @kissabel_apples from @jewelosco declaring they are brightly colored inside, and I went to cut an apple for my toddler yesterday morning and gasped. It was pink! Vibrant pink from edge to edge. I peeked back in our pantry and grabbed a gala apple instead, quickly running a lemon over the cut edge of the kissabel apple and wrapping it up. “Sorry,” I told my son, “this one’s for mama.”⁣
⁣
Earlier in the week, I was watching a course on food photography from @evakosmasflores and a lesson on including yourself in frame. I know how to do it, of course, but I feel like I never have the idea to include myself in my compositions. ⁣
⁣
Two days ago, as I put away laundry basket after laundry basket of clothes I happened to notice this pink and red dress I don’t remember buying. Huh, I thought, this could be pretty for something.⁣
⁣
Last night as I wrapped up client work, I observed my studio and peeked my head out the door. “You got him? Can I do one for me?” I asked my husband, “before bedtime?” ⁣
⁣
This might have felt like a bit of a race against the clock before bedtime stories, with a three year old asking to play hide and seek while I worked out composition, but it was worth it. Leaning into moments of inspiration, even under less than ideal circumstances. If I always wait for there to be no client work on the docket, the laundry to be put away, the kid in bed, the studio pristine… I will never capitalize on the opportunity trying to show itself. So find a minute. Throw the dress on. Set the scene. And get in the frame 💕⁣
⁣

It hit me the other day. Some inadvertent math I hadn’t planned on subconsciously doing while browsing the shelves at Target. This is the tenth Christmas since everything changed. ⁣
⁣
I remember Christmas Eve with you for the greater part of my life, having a coffee or tea toward the end of the night. Maybe you still had wrapping to do— God knows the presents over flowed from under the tree every year. Thoughtful gifts and items of necessity, you knew just what we needed every time. ⁣
⁣
But just like that there was a last Christmas. A last morning spent in North Andover. A thousand lasts and a million changes as time trudged on through my desperate and grayest winter days.⁣
⁣
And you’re right here before me⁣
But you’re also long gone⁣
The shell of you becoming routine yet leaving me shocked for a decade— just wanting to give you a hug ⁣
To transfer the comfort I’d felt for thirty years back up the chain⁣
Becoming a mother while mothering my own.⁣
⁣
I think I finally get it. I observe my own hands as they wrap gift after gift and roll out cookie dough and I know you were doing those things for me, for others, your love language always being a most fluent giving of gifts, flourished with tags in a script that so closely matches my own. ⁣
⁣
Thirty magical christmases with you, and I never knew I was learning to make the magic— the mom magic— all along. ♥️⁣
